    "treatments": "Treatment for pericarditis often depends on the underlying cause. Nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs), such as ibuprofen or aspirin, are commonly prescribed to relieve pain and reduce inflammation. In viral cases, symptomatic treatment may be sufficient, while bacterial infections may require antibiotics. If the condition is due to autoimmune diseases, corticosteroids may be employed to control inflammation. In more severe cases or recurrent pericarditis that does not respond to medications, a procedure called pericardiocentesis may be necessary to drain excess fluid from the pericardial space. Long-term management may involve monitoring and addressing any underlying heart conditions."
